[[File:Knud Arne Jürgensen Portræt (jpeg).JPG|thumb]] {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Knud Arne Jürgensen | honorific_suffix = | image_size =Knud Arne Jürgensen Portræt (jpeg).JPG | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1952}} | birth_place = Copenhagen | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | resting_place = | monuments = | residence = [[Copenhagen]] | nationality = Danish | other_names = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Copenhagen]] | occupation = | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = [[Dance, music, opera and theatre history]] | notable_works = | style = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | movement = | opponents = | boards = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | callsign = | awards = Knight (Cavaliere) of the Italian Republic | website = [http://www.knudarnejurgensen.dk/ '''www.knudarnejurgensen.dk'''] | signature = | signature_alt = | footnotes = | ethnicity = | religion = | relations = | box_width = | misc = }}
'''Knud Arne Jürgensen''' (born 1952) is a Danish music-, opera-, ballet- and theater historian, dramaturg, curator of exhibitions, senior researcher, dr. phil.
== Biography == Jürgensen studied music and theater history at the University of Copenhagen from 1975 and for seven years, but had previously to his studies in musicology studied piano with professor [http://www.kvinfo.dk/side/597/bio/1541/origin/170/ Galina Werschenska] and later at the [[Royal Danish Academy of Music]] in Copenhagen. The combination of research in the fields of music, theater and dance has followed him since.
During two periods in the late 1980s and mid-1990s, Knud Arne Jürgensen was a research fellow of the Danish [[Carlsberg Foundation]]. The work resulted in three English-language monographs on the Danish dancer, choreographer and ballet master [[August Bournonville]], on whom Jürgensen has continued to work extensively which his considerable [http://www.knudarnejurgensen.dk/home/bibliography list of publications] and several exhibitions testify to. An international theme exhibition at the [[Royal Danish Library]], and a poster exhibition at The [[Royal Danish Theatre]] were carried out in the Bournonville jubilee-year 2005 marking the bicentenary of his birth.
When Knud Arne Jürgensen in 1997 made his doctoral thesis (dr. phil., equivalent to Doctor of Music), it was with a music and theater historical thesis on the composer [[Giuseppe Verdi]] and the ballets in his operas, which resulted in Verdi ballet performances at the [[Berlin State Opera]] in 1999 (the ballet "Verdiana") and the [http://www.wiener-staatsoper.at/Content.Node/home/Startseite-Content.de.php Vienna State Opera] in 2001 ("Verdi Ballet: Ein Maskenball"). He has furthermore written in-depth biographies of danish theater critics [[Herman Bang]], [[Frederik Schyberg]] and [[Jens Kistrup]] and was chief editor and program author when the complete orchestral works by danish composer [[Hans Christian Lumbye]] were recorded during the period 1998-2004. In addition, he has reconstructed a number of forgotten choreographies of August Bournonville following the choreographer's original records.
Knud Arne Jürgensen was also co-editor of the orchetral scores for the Bournonville ballet ''[[A Folk Tale (Et folkesagn)]]'' and a number of [http://www.kb.dk/en/nb/dcm/udgivelser/lumbye/index.html Lumbye works] as a gift from the [[Royal Danish Library]] to Her Majesty [[Queen Margrethe II]] on her 60th birthday in 2000 and 70th birthday in 2010. Recently he has edited the CD-recording of Lumbye-works ''Fredensborgdage'' for the Royal Danish Lifeguards as a present on the occasion of Her Majesty [[Queen Margrethe II's]] 75th birthday in 2015.
== Professional career == Jürgensen was from 1998 to 2010 Head of the [[Drama Collection]], research librarian, senior researcher and subject specialist in theater and performing arts at the [[Royal Danish Library]]. Since 2010, he has worked as exhibition curator, senior researcher and subject specialist at the Copenhagen [[Theatre Museum in the Court Theatre]], where he has completed his most recent monographs on the late Danish theater critic Jens Kistrup, (published in 2012), and the first complete and annotated edition of the plays by Danish impressionist writer, Herman Bang (published in 2016).
He has also been a Fellow at the [http://www.acdan.it/ Danish Academy in Rome] from 2011 to 2012, where he has been working on editing and publishing the score for the Italian baroque opera ''[http://www.edizioniquasar.it/sku.php?id_libro=1970 Il Valdemaro]'' by the Neapolitan composer [[Domenico Sarro]], a work that represents one of the earliest operas based on a Scandinavian theme, and which appeared for the first time on print in a new critical edition in 2013.
Knud Arne Jürgensen, who has been a member and trustee of several professional boards, has published more than 30 Danish and international monographs in the field of music history and the performing arts and well over hundred scientific papers and essays. He has curated more than 20 Danish and international thematic exhibitions, guest lectured at the [http://www.ku.dk/english University of Copenhagen] as well as at a large number of foreign universities, museums and theater institutions in the United States, Russia, Austria, Italy, France and Germany.
