{{Infobox artist | name = Mark Tribe | image = Marktribe.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Mark Tribe | birth_name = | birth_date = 1966 | birth_place = San Francisco | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = USA | field = [[Conceptual art]], [[installation art]], [[video art]] | training = Brown University, University of California, San Diego | movement = | works = | patrons = | influenced by = | influenced = | awards = }}
'''Mark Tribe''' (born 1966, [[San Francisco]], California) is an [[United States|American]] [[artist]] who lives and works in [[New York City]].<ref name=Artforum>{{cite journal|last=Bryan-Wilson|first=Julia|title=Sounding the fury: Julia Bryan-Wilson on Kirsten Forkert and Mark Tribe|journal=Artforum International|date=January 2008|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Sounding+the+fury%3A+Julia+Bryan-Wilson+on+Kirsten+Forkert+and+Mark...-a0173789255|accessdate=August 28, 2011}}</ref> He is the founder of [[Rhizome (organization)|Rhizome]], a not-for-profit arts organization based in [[New York City]].<ref name="NYT Mirapaul">{{cite news|last=Mirapaul|first=Matthew|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/library/tech/98/04/cyber/artsatlarge/02artsatlarge.html|accessdate=August 28, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 2, 1998|title=Art Site Takes Plunge Into Not-for-Profitability}}</ref>
In 2013, he was appointed chair of the MFA program of the [[School of Visual Arts]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artandeducation.net/announcement/sva-announces-appointments-of-steven-henry-madoff-mark-tribe-and-new-ma-in-curatorial-practice/|title=SVA announces appointments of Steven Henry Madoff, Mark Tribe and New MA in Curatorial Practice {{!}} Art & Education|website=Art & Education|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> Formerly, he was Assistant Professor of Modern Culture and Media Studies at [[Brown University]],<ref name=Kennedy>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Randy|title=Giving New Life to Protests of Yore|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/28/arts/design/28mall.html?ex=1343361600&en=ae3bc6d9644cfbc9&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink|accessdate=August 28, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 28, 2007}}</ref> Director of the Digital Media Center at the [[Columbia University School of the Arts]], and Visiting Assistant Professor and Artist in Residence at [[Williams College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/news/mark-tribe-will-chair-fine-arts-mfa-at-sva/|title=Mark Tribe Will Chair Fine Arts MFA at SVA - News - Art in America|website=www.artinamericamagazine.com|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> He is the author of ''The Port Huron Project: Reenactments of Historic Protest Speeches'' (Charta, 2010)<ref name=Charta>{{cite web |url=http://www.chartaartbooks.it/index.php?page=shop.product_details&category_id=14&flypage=charta_flypage&product_id=880&option=com_virtuemart&Itemid=42&lang=en_US |title=Charta Art Books - Mark Tribe |accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref> and the co-author of ''New Media Art'' (Taschen, 2006).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/151642.New_Media_Art |title=New Media Art |accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref> He received an MFA in Visual Art from the [[University of California, San Diego]] in [[La Jolla]], California in 1994 and an AB in Visual Art from [[Brown University]] in 1990.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://momaps1.org/studio-visit/artist/mark-tribe-0|title=Mark Tribe {{!}} P.S.1 Studio Visit|website=momaps1.org|access-date=2016-09-24}}</ref>
== Work ==
Tribe's drawings, performances, installations and photographs often deal with social and political issues.<ref name="Charta" /> His work has been featured in solo exhibitions at the [[Corcoran Gallery of Art]] in Washington, D.C.;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/museums-galleries/article/13045850/mark-tribes-plein-air-at-the-corcoran-reviewed|title=Mark Tribe's "Plein Air" at the Corcoran, Reviewed|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> Momenta Art in Brooklyn, New York;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/-mark-tribe/|title=Mark Tribe - Reviews - Art in America|website=www.artinamericamagazine.com|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> [[Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions]] (LACE) in Los Angeles, California;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2009/10/port-huron-project-lace.html|title=Port Huron Project videos on view at LACE|date=2009-10-20|website=LA Times Blogs - Culture Monster|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> and DiverseWorks in Houston, Texas.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.digicult.it/news/chelsea-knight-mark-tribe-posse-comitatus/|title=Chelsea Knight and Mark Tribe - Posse Comitatus|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> His work has been included in group exhibitions at the [[Queens Museum]] in [[New York City]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queensmuseum.org/2016intl/responses/uneven-development-on-beirut-and-plein-air|title=Uneven Development: On Beirut and Plein Air|last=Ruiz|first=Alan|date=2016|website=www.queensmuseum.org|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> the [[Palais de Tokyo]] in [[Paris]];<ref name=":0" /> the [[Menil Collection]] in [[Houston]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aurorapictureshow.org/print.asp?pageid=83&calid=918&galid=&fid=|title=Mark Tribe: The Port Huron Project|website=aurorapictureshow.org|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref> [[Centre Georges Pompidou]] in Paris;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.azzellini.net/en/film/que-faire-art-film-politiqu