[[Image:Map of Vedic India.png|thumb|300px|The approximate extent of the [[Vedic period]] ''Āryāvarta'' is highlighted in pale yellow]] '''Āryāvarta''' ([[Sanskrit]]: आर्यावर्त, lit. "abode of the noble or excellent ones (Aryas)",<ref>[http://www.sanskrit-lexicon.uni-koeln.de/scans/MWScan/2014/web/webtc/indexcaller.php?input=HK&output=SktRomanUnicode&citation=AryAvarta Aryavarta], Monier Williams Sanskrit English Dictionary (1899)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dsalsrv04.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/apte_query.py?page=356|title=Revised and Enlarged Edition of Prin. V. S. Apte's The Practical Sanskrit-English Dictionary|last=Apte|first=Vaman Shivaram|date=1957|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref> {{IPA-sa|aːɾjaːˈʋəɾtə}}) is a term for parts of the [[Indian subcontinent]] in the ancient [[Hindu texts]] such as [[Dharmasastra|''Dharmashastras'']] and ''Sutras''. The limits of ''Aryavarta'' varies from text to text.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Handbuch der Orientalistik: Indien|last=Scharfe|first=Hartmut|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=9004090606|location=|pages=12|language=en}}</ref> These texts also name other parts of the Indian subcontinent as ''Brahmavarta'', ''Madhyadesha'', ''Panchala'' and others, with neither clear boundaries nor details about who lived in them.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
==Classical sources== The ''[[Manu Smriti|Manusmṛti]]'' (2.22) gives the name to "the tract between the [[Himalayas|Himalaya]] and the [[Vindhya Range|Vindhya ranges]], from the Eastern Sea ([[Bay of Bengal]]) to the Western Sea ([[Arabian Sea]])".<ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= 70|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref><ref>[[Michael Cook (historian)|Michael Cook]] (2014), ''Ancient Religions, Modern Politics: The Islamic Case in Comparative Perspective'', Princeton University Press, p.68: "Aryavarta [...] is defined by Manu as extending from the Himalayas in the north to the Vindhyas of Central India in the south and from the sea in the west to the sea in the east."</ref>
The ''[[Kalpa (Vedanga)#Dharma Sutras|Vasistha Dharma Sutra]]'' I.8-9 and 12-13 locates the Āryāvarta to the west of the disappearance of the [[Sarasvati River]] in the desert and Arabian sea, to the east of the Kālakavana, to the south of the [[Pariyatra Mountains]] and the Vindhya Range and to the north of the Himalayas.{{sfn|Neelis|2010|p=194}}
The [[Baudhayana sutras|Baudhayana ''Dharmasutra'' (BDS) 1.1.2.10]] gives similar definitions and declares that Āryāvarta is the land that lies west of Kālakavana, east of [[Adarsana]], south of the [[Himalayas]] and north of the Vindhyas, but in BDS 1.1.2.11 Āryāvarta is confined to the [[doab]] of the [[Ganges]]-[[Yamuna]], and BDS 1.1.2.13-15. [[Patanjali]]'s {{IAST|[[Mahābhāṣya]]}}{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}} defines Āryāvarta like the ''Vasistha [[Dharmaśāstra|Dharmasutra]]''.
The [[Gurjara-Pratihara]] king in the tenth century was titled the ''Maharajadhiraja of Aryavarta''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Al-Hind: Early medieval India and the expansion of Islam, 7th-11th centuries|author=André Wink|publisher=BRILL|year=2002|isbn=978-0-391-04173-8|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=g2m7_R5P2oAC&pg=PA284&dq|page=284}}</ref>
